  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In this work, a study of the average transverse momentum ( <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">T</mi></mrow></msub></math> ) as a function of the mid-rapidity charged hadron multiplicity ( <math altimg="si34.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">ch</mi></mrow></msub></math> ) and hadron mass ( m ) in p–Pb and Pb–Pb collisions at LHC energies is presented. For the events producing low <math altimg="si34.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">ch</mi></mrow></msub></math> , the average <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">T</mi></mrow></msub></math> is found to scale with the reduced hadron mass, i.e., mass divided by the number of quark constituents ( <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">q</mi></mrow></msub></math> ), this scaling also holds for inelastic pp collisions at RHIC and LHC energies. The scaling is broken in high multiplicity p–Pb and Pb–Pb collisions, where, for <math altimg="si6.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">〈</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">d</mi><msub><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">ch</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">d</mi><mi>η</mi><mo stretchy="false">〉</mo><mo>≲</mo><mn>60</mn></math> the average <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">T</mi></mrow></msub></math> is higher for baryons than that for mesons, though they increase linearly with <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">q</mi></mrow></msub></math> . This behavior is qualitatively well reproduced by Pythia 8, but not by hydro calculations, where an universal scaling with the hadron mass (and not with <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">q</mi></mrow></msub></math> ) is predicted for all the multiplicity event classes. Only the central (0–60%) Pb–Pb collisions behave as expected from hydro.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
  </datafield>
